{"title_page": "Orlando Brandes", "text_new": "{{short description|21st-century Brazilian Catholic bishop}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = Archbishop\n| honorific-prefix = The Most Reverend\n| name = Orlando Brandes\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aparecida|Archbishop of Aparecida]]\n| image = Orlando Brandes em Missa do Dia de Nossa Senhora Aparecida em 2019.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Orlando Brandes in the Mass of the Day of Our Lady of Aparecida in 2019.\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church = [[Catholic Church in Brazil|Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aparecida|Aparecida]]\n| province = S\u00e3o Paulo\n| metropolis = Aparecida\n| diocese = \n| see = Aparecida\n| appointed = 16 November 2016\n| enthroned = 21 January 2017\n| term = \n| quashed = \n| predecessor = [[Raymundo Damasceno Assis]]\n| successor = \n| opposed = \n| previous_post = {{unbulleted list|Bishop of Joinville (1994\u20132006)|Archbishop of Londrina (2006-2016)}}\n<!---------- Orders ---------->| ordination = 6 July 1974\n| ordained_by = \n| consecration = 5 June 1994\n| consecrated_by = [[Jo\u00e3o Oneres Marchiori]]\n| cardinal = \n| created_cardinal_by = \n| rank = [[Archbishop]]\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->| birth_name = Orlando Brandes\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1944|04|13}}\n| birth_place = Urubici, Santa Catarina, Brazil\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| buried = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality = [[Brazil]]ian\n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence = \n| parents = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| motto = ''Somos Oper\u00e1rios de Deus''<br/>(We are God's workers)\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| coat_of_arms = Coat_of_arms_of_Orlando_Brandes.jpg\n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\n{{Infobox bishopstyles\n|    name=Orlando Brandes\n|    dipstyle=[[The Most Reverend]]\n|    offstyle=[[Your Excellency]]\n|    relstyle=[[Archbishop]]\n|    deathstyle=\n|    image = Coat_of_arms_of_Orlando_Brandes.jpg\n|    image_size = 200px\n}}\n'''Orlando Brandes''' (born 13 April 1944) is a [[Brazil]]ian [[prelate]] of the [[Catholic Church]] who has served as the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aparecida|Archbishop of Aparecida]] since 2017. He was [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Joinville|Bishop of Joinville]] from 1994 to 2006 and [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Londrina|Archbishop of Londrina]] from 2006 to 2016.\n\n==Early life==\nBrandes was born on 13 April 1944 in [[Urubici]], Brazil. He completed his primary and secondary studies in Urubici and [[Lages]].  He studied Philosophy in [[Curitiba]], then did his theological studies at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in Rome.  He did post-graduate studies in [[Christian ethics|moral theology]] in Rome.<ref name=pr10052006/>\n\nBrandes was ordained priest on 6 July 1974 in [[Francisco Beltr\u00e3o]]. As a priest, he exercised the following duties: Professor of Theology at the [[Institute of Theology of Santa Catarina]]; Rector of the Major Seminary in [[Florian\u00f3polis]]; Preacher of Spiritual Retreats; Director of the Institute of Theology of Santa Catarina; Member of the Ecclesiastical Court of Florian\u00f3polis; lecturer and preacher of missions.<ref name=pr10052006/>\n\n==Bishop and archbishop==\nOn 9 March 1994, [[Pope John Paul II]] appointed Brandes [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Joinville|Bishop of Joinville]]. He received his episcopal ordination there on 5 June 1994<ref name=diobio>{{cite web | language = pt |access-date = 10 April 2019| title = Arquidiocese \u2013 Arcebispo | date= 31 January 2017 |url = https://arqaparecida.org.br/Arquidiocese/Arcebispo | website= Archdiocese of Aparecida }}</ref> from Bishops [[Jo\u00e3o Oneres Marchiori]], [[Eusebio Oscar Scheid]], SCI and [[Greg\u00f3rio Warmeling]]. He was secretary of the south region of the [[National Conference of Bishops of Brazil]].\n\nOn 10 May 2006, Pope Benedict XVI appointed Brandes as Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Londrina|Londrina]].<ref name=pr10052006>{{cite press release | language = it |url=http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2006/05/10/0241/00686.html |title=Rinunce e Nomine, 10.05.2006 |publisher= [[Holy See Press Office]] |date=10 May 2006 |accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> where he was installed on 23 July.<ref name=diobio/>\n\nOn 16 November 2016, [[Pope Francis]] appointed him Archbishop of Aparecida.<ref>{{cite press release |language= it | url= http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2016/11/16/0827/01850.html |title=Rinunce e nomine, 16.11.2016 |publisher= Holy See Press Office |date=16 November 2016 |accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> He was installed as Archbishop of Aparecida on 21 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news | language= pt | access-date = 18 April 2019 | date = 21 January 2017 | url = http://g1.globo.com/sp/vale-do-paraiba-regiao/noticia/2017/01/dom-orlando-brandes-assume-cargo-de-novo-arcebispo-de-aparecida-sp.html | last= Poliana | first = Lorena |title=Dom Orlando Brandes assume cargo de novo arcebispo de Aparecida, SP| publisher = G1 Vale do Para\u00edba e Regi\u00e3o}}</ref> In October 12, 2019, during the [[Synod of Bishops for the Pan-Amazon region|Amazon Synod]], he drew national attention for giving a sermon in Aparecida in a [[Morning]] [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] condemning what he saw as an \"violent\" and \"unjust\" right wing ideology, a \"dragon of traditionialism\" which he saw as \"firing on the Pope [Francis], on the [Amazon] Synod, and the Second Vatican Council\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Aparecida recebe milhares de fi\u00e9is; Arcebispo fala em \"direita violenta\" |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/brasil/aparecida-recebe-milhares-de-fieis-arcebispo-fala-em-direita-violenta/ |accessdate=12 October 2019 |agency=Exame |publisher=Abril |date=12 October 2019}}</ref> a few hours later, the [[President of Brazil]] [[Jair Bolsonaro]], known for being [[Political right]], went to Mass in the National Shrine of Aparecida at 4 pm and read the biblical text as [[Reader (liturgy)|Reader]].<ref>[https://br.blastingnews.com/brasil/2019/10/bolsonaro-faz-leitura-em-missa-de-aparecida-presidida-pelo-arcebispo-dom-orlando-brandes-002999829.html Bolsonaro faz leitura em missa em Aparecida presidida pelo arcebispo Dom Orlando Brandes ]</ref><ref>[https://www.a12.com/santuario/noticias/jair-bolsonaro-participa-dos-festejos-da-padroeira-do-brasil-em-aparecida Jair Bolsonaro participa dos festejos da Padroeira do Brasil em Aparecida]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | language = pt | title = Arquidiocese \u2013 Arcebispo | date= 31 January 2017 |url = https://arqaparecida.org.br/Arquidiocese/Arcebispo |website= Archdiocese of Aparecida }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{s-bef|before=Greg\u00f3rio Warmeling|years=1957-1994}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Joinville|Bishop of Joinville]]|years=1994-2006}}\n{{s-aft|after=Ireneu Roque Scherer|years=2006-present}}\n{{s-bef|before=Albano Bortoletto Cavallin|years=1992-2006}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Londrina|Archbishop of Londrina]]|years=2006-2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Geremias Steinmetz]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Raymundo Damasceno Assis]]|years=2004-2016}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aparecida|Archbishop of Aparecida]]|years=2016-present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Brazil}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brandes, Orlando}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Gregorian University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|21st-century Brazilian Catholic bishop}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = Archbishop\n| honorific-prefix = The Most Reverend\n| name = Orlando Brandes\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aparecida|Archbishop of Aparecida]]\n| image = Orlando Brandes em Missa do Dia de Nossa Senhora Aparecida em 2019.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Orlando Brandes in the Mass of the Day of Our Lady of Aparecida in 2019.\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church = [[Catholic Church in Brazil|Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aparecida|Aparecida]]\n| province = S\u00e3o Paulo\n| metropolis = Aparecida\n| diocese = \n| see = Aparecida\n| appointed = 16 November 2016\n| enthroned = 21 January 2017\n| term = \n| quashed = \n| predecessor = [[Raymundo Damasceno Assis]]\n| successor = \n| opposed = \n| previous_post = {{unbulleted list|Bishop of Joinville (1994\u20132006)|Archbishop of Londrina (2006-2016)}}\n<!---------- Orders ---------->| ordination = 6 July 1974\n| ordained_by = \n| consecration = 5 June 1994\n| consecrated_by = [[Jo\u00e3o Oneres Marchiori]]\n| cardinal = \n| created_cardinal_by = \n| rank = [[Archbishop]]\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->| birth_name = Orlando Brandes\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1944|04|13}}\n| birth_place = Urubici, Santa Catarina, Brazil\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| buried = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality = [[Brazil]]ian\n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence = \n| parents = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| motto = ''Somos Oper\u00e1rios de Deus''<br/>(We are God's workers)\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| coat_of_arms = Coat_of_arms_of_Orlando_Brandes.jpg\n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\n{{Infobox bishopstyles\n|    name=Orlando Brandes\n|    dipstyle=[[The Most Reverend]]\n|    offstyle=[[Your Excellency]]\n|    relstyle=[[Archbishop]]\n|    deathstyle=\n|    image = Coat_of_arms_of_Orlando_Brandes.jpg\n|    image_size = 200px\n}}\n'''Orlando Brandes''' (born 13 April 1944) is a [[Brazil]]ian [[prelate]] of the [[Catholic Church]] who has served as the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aparecida|Archbishop of Aparecida]] since 2017. He was [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Joinville|Bishop of Joinville]] from 1994 to 2006 and [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Londrina|Archbishop of Londrina]] from 2006 to 2016.\n\n==Early life==\nBrandes was born on 13 April 1944 in [[Urubici]], Brazil. He completed his primary and secondary studies in Urubici and [[Lages]].  He studied Philosophy in [[Curitiba]], then did his theological studies at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in Rome.  He did post-graduate studies in [[Christian ethics|moral theology]] in Rome.<ref name=pr10052006/>\n\nBrandes was ordained priest on 6 July 1974 in [[Francisco Beltr\u00e3o]]. As a priest, he exercised the following duties: Professor of Theology at the [[Institute of Theology of Santa Catarina]]; Rector of the Major Seminary in [[Florian\u00f3polis]]; Preacher of Spiritual Retreats; Director of the Institute of Theology of Santa Catarina; Member of the Ecclesiastical Court of Florian\u00f3polis; lecturer and preacher of missions.<ref name=pr10052006/>\n\n==Bishop and archbishop==\nOn 9 March 1994, [[Pope John Paul II]] appointed Brandes [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Joinville|Bishop of Joinville]]. He received his episcopal ordination there on 5 June 1994<ref name=diobio>{{cite web | language = pt |access-date = 10 April 2019| title = Arquidiocese \u2013 Arcebispo | date= 31 January 2017 |url = https://arqaparecida.org.br/Arquidiocese/Arcebispo | website= Archdiocese of Aparecida }}</ref> from Bishops [[Jo\u00e3o Oneres Marchiori]], [[Eusebio Oscar Scheid]], SCI and [[Greg\u00f3rio Warmeling]]. He was secretary of the south region of the [[National Conference of Bishops of Brazil]].\n\nOn 10 May 2006, Pope Benedict XVI appointed Brandes as Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Londrina|Londrina]].<ref name=pr10052006>{{cite press release | language = it ||url=http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2006/05/10/0241/00686.html |title=Rinunce e Nomine, 10.05.2006 |publisher= [[Holy See Press Office]] |date=10 May 2006 |accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> where he was installed on 23 July.<ref name=diobio/>\n\nOn 16 November 2016, [[Pope Francis]] appointed him Archbishop of Aparecida.<ref>{{cite press release |language= it | url= http://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2016/11/16/0827/01850.html |title=Rinunce e nomine, 16.11.2016 |publisher= Holy See Press Office |date=16 November 2016 |accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> He was installed as Archbishop of Aparecida on 21 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news | language= pt | access-date = 18 April 2019 | date = 21 January 2017 | url = http://g1.globo.com/sp/vale-do-paraiba-regiao/noticia/2017/01/dom-orlando-brandes-assume-cargo-de-novo-arcebispo-de-aparecida-sp.html | last= Poliana | first = Lorena |title=Dom Orlando Brandes assume cargo de novo arcebispo de Aparecida, SP| publisher = G1 Vale do Para\u00edba e Regi\u00e3o}}</ref> In October 12 2019, during the [[Synod_of_Bishops_for_the_Pan-Amazon_region|Amazon Synod]], he drew national attention for giving a sermon in Aparecida in a [[Morning]] [[Mass]] condemning what he saw as an \"violent\" and \"unjust\" right wing ideology, a \"dragon of traditionialism\" which he saw as \"firing on the Pope [Francis], on the [Amazon] Synod, and the Second Vatican Council\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Aparecida recebe milhares de fi\u00e9is; Arcebispo fala em \u201cdireita violenta\u201d |url=https://exame.abril.com.br/brasil/aparecida-recebe-milhares-de-fieis-arcebispo-fala-em-direita-violenta/ |accessdate=12 October 2019 |agency=Exame |publisher=Abril |date=12 October 2019}}</ref> a few hours later, the [[President of Brazil]] [[Jair Bolsonaro]], known for being [[Political right]], went to Mass in the National Shrine of Aparecida at 4 pm and read the biblical text as [[Reader (liturgy)|Reader]].<ref>[https://br.blastingnews.com/brasil/2019/10/bolsonaro-faz-leitura-em-missa-de-aparecida-presidida-pelo-arcebispo-dom-orlando-brandes-002999829.html Bolsonaro faz leitura em missa em Aparecida presidida pelo arcebispo Dom Orlando Brandes ]</ref><ref>[https://www.a12.com/santuario/noticias/jair-bolsonaro-participa-dos-festejos-da-padroeira-do-brasil-em-aparecida Jair Bolsonaro participa dos festejos da Padroeira do Brasil em Aparecida]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | language = pt | title = Arquidiocese \u2013 Arcebispo | date= 31 January 2017 |url = https://arqaparecida.org.br/Arquidiocese/Arcebispo |website= Archdiocese of Aparecida }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{s-bef|before=Greg\u00f3rio Warmeling|years=1957-1994}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Joinville|Bishop of Joinville]]|years=1994-2006}}\n{{s-aft|after=Ireneu Roque Scherer|years=2006-present}}\n{{s-bef|before=Albano Bortoletto Cavallin|years=1992-2006}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Londrina|Archbishop of Londrina]]|years=2006-2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Geremias Steinmetz]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Raymundo Damasceno Assis]]|years=2004-2016}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Aparecida|Archbishop of Aparecida]]|years=2016-present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Brazil}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brandes, Orlando}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Gregorian University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix wikilinks, replaced:Mass\u2192Mass", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orlando_Brandes"}
{"title_page": "Lester D. Mallory", "text_new": "[[Image:Lester-D-Mallory-127K.jpg|thumb|right|Ambassador Lester D. Mallory]]\n\n'''Lester DeWitt Mallory''' (April 21, 1904 \u2013 June 21, 1994) was an American [[Diplomacy|diplomat]].\n\nMallory was born in [[Houlton, Maine]]. He received a [[Academic degree|bachelor of science]] in agriculture in 1927 and a master of science in agriculture degree in 1929 from the [[University of British Columbia]].  Mallory earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[agricultural economics]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1935.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Biographic Register of the Department of State''</ref>\n\nThe son of Enrique and May Mallory, Mallory spent his early years in Oregon, Alberta, and British Columbia, and attended Naramota and Oak Bay High Schools in British Columbia from 1919 to 1922.<ref name=\"copy\">Copy of biographic sketch submitted to the Farm Credit Administration of Berkeley dated April 6, 1938,  in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref>  From 1927 to 1928 Mallory was an assistant in horticulture at the University of British Columbia, and in 1929 worked as secretary of the British Columbia Fruit Growers.<ref>Biography, dated July 1, 1930, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref>\n\nMallory began working for the United States [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] in 1931, initially for the [[United States Department of Agriculture|Department of Agriculture]] as assistant [[Commissioner#U.S._Department_of_Agriculture|agricultural commissioner]] in Marseille, to which position he was appointed June 15, 1931.<ref name=\"prob-rpt\">Report on Probationary Appointee, Standard Form No. 17, dated November 14, 1931, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref> Mallory was selected for this position on the basis of his expertise in analysis of horticultural products.<ref name=\"nils-memo\">Memorandum for the Secretary, dated March 26, 1931, from Nils A. Olsen, Chief, Bureau of Agricultural Economics, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref> \n\nFrom July 1933 to August 1934 Mallory was assigned to Washington as an associate agricultural economist in the Agricultural Adjustment Administration of USDA, working on farm credit issues.<ref name=\"prob-rpt\"/><ref>Application for Employment, Farm Credit Administration of Berkeley, dated April 6, 1938, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref>  In August 1934 he was assigned to Paris as assistant [[agricultural attach\u00e9]].  Effective June 2, 1938, he was designated acting agricultural attach\u00e9, and as of June 1, 1939, he was appointed agricultural attach\u00e9 at Paris.<ref>Memorandum for Mr. Roy F. Hendrickson from L.A. Wheeler dated May 3, 1939, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref>  \n\n[[Image:390519 Wallace appt Mallory agatt.JPG|thumb|left|Letter from Secretary of Agriculture Henry Wallace to the Secretary of State advising of Mallory's appointment as agricultural attach\u00e9 at Paris. Source: National Archives and Records Administration]]\n\nMallory was evacuated to the United States with the outbreak of World War II in September 1939 and reassigned as the first U.S. agricultural attach\u00e9 in Mexico City.  At that time he was commissioned a [[Foreign Service Officer]] in the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]], as the [[Foreign Agricultural Service]] was abolished and agricultural attach\u00e9s were transferred from USDA to State in that year. \n\nMallory subsequently served in liberated Paris, from Christmas Eve 1944 until mid-1945. During his tour of duty in Paris, Mallory was granted permission by the Department of State to marry a foreign national, Eleanor Mercedes Struck y Bulnes, whom he had met in Mexico City.<ref>This correspondence is stored in Mallory's personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref>   He then returned to the U.S., where he was liaison officer between USDA's Office of Foreign Agricultural Relations and the U.S. Department of State.  Mallory was assigned to [[Havana]] as counselor of embassy (deputy chief of mission) in 1947 and in 1949 to [[Buenos Aires]] in the same capacity.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>Foreign Service Operations Memorandum dated June 13, 1949, regarding departure from post of Lester D. MALLORY, FSO, in the personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref>  On August 23, 1950, President Truman appointed Mallory to the personal rank of Minister.<ref name=nara-annex>Letter to Lester D. Mallory from Harry S Truman dated August 23, 1950, personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref>\n\nMallory served as [[United States Ambassador to Jordan|Ambassador to Jordan]] from 1953 to 1958 and to [[United States Ambassador to Guatemala|Guatemala]] in 1958 and 1959. During his tour of duty in Jordan, on July 20, 1955, Mallory was promoted to the then-highest Foreign Service rank, [[Senior_Foreign_Service#History|Career Minister]].<ref>Notification of Personnel Action dated July 20, 1955, \"Promotion to Class of Career Minister,\" personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref>  Mallory was a [[Assistant Secretary of State for Western Hemisphere Affairs|Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for Western Hemisphere Affairs]] in 1960 and retired from the State Department on October 31 of that year.<ref>Letter from Christian A. Herter to Lester Mallory dated October 14, 1960, personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref> \n\nMallory then joined the [[Inter-American Development Bank]], working in Washington, D.C., [[Costa Rica]], and [[Panama]], and helped establish the [[anthropology]] department at the [[University of Guadalajara]], Mexico.  In 1961 the Guatemalan government presented him with the [[Order of the Quetzal]].<ref>''FAS Letter'', April 1961</ref>\n\nHe lived in [[Lake Forest, California]] and died following a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at Saddleback Hospital in [[Laguna Hills, California]].  The conference room of the Foreign Agricultural Service's office in the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City is named in his honor. His oral history interview was published by the Association for Diplomatic Studies and Training.\n\n\n\n=== His role in the embargo against Cuba ===\n\nAs Deputy Assistant Secretary, he wrote an internal memo on April 6, 1960 to initiate the embargo against Cuba. Mallory proposed starving Cuba denying money and supplies to Cuba, decreasing their wages, and bringing about hunger and desperation. Later that year, the Eisenhower administration instituted the embargo.\n\nIn a memorandum, declassified in 1991, Mallory wrote \"Most Cubans support Castro\u2026There is no effective political opposition.The only possible way to make the government lose domestic support is by provoking disappointment and discouragement through economic dissatisfaction and hardships every possible means should be immediately used to weaken the economic life denying Cuba funds and supplies to reduce nominal and real salaries with the objective of provoking hunger, desperation and the overthrow of the government\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{NARA}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web| title=Association for Diplomatic Studies and Training Oral Histories | url=http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/collections/diplomacy/ | accessdate=2009-03-23}} (use the search engine for a \"Full Text\" search on \"Lester Mallory\" in quotes)\n* {{cite web | title=Direct Link to Oral History of Lester D. Mallory | url=http://www.adst.org/OH%20TOCs/Mallory,%20Lester%20.toc.pdf | accessdate=2016-09-06}}\n* {{cite web| title=Lester Mallory, 90, Former U.S. Envoy (obituary) | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/02/world/lester-mallory-90-former-us-envoy.html | publisher=New York Times | date=July 2, 1994 }}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Joseph C. Green]] | after=[[Parker T. Hart]] | title=[[United States Ambassador to Jordan]] | years=December 1, 1953&ndash;January 11, 1958}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Edward J. Sparks]] | after=[[John J. Muccio]] | title=[[United States Ambassador to Guatemala]] | years=February 27, 1958&ndash;November 11, 1959}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mallory, Lester DeWitt}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Jordan]]\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:Order of the Quetzal]]\n[[Category:United States Foreign Service personnel]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Lester-D-Mallory-127K.jpg|thumb|right|Ambassador Lester D. Mallory]]\n\n'''Lester DeWitt Mallory''' (April 21, 1904 \u2013 June 21, 1994) was an American [[Diplomacy|diplomat]].\n\nMallory was born in [[Houlton, Maine]]. He received a [[Academic degree|bachelor of science]] in agriculture in 1927 and a master of science in agriculture degree in 1929 from the [[University of British Columbia]].  Mallory earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[agricultural economics]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1935.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Biographic Register of the Department of State''</ref>\n\nThe son of Enrique and May Mallory, Mallory spent his early years in Oregon, Alberta, and British Columbia, and attended Naramota and Oak Bay High Schools in British Columbia from 1919 to 1922.<ref name=\"copy\">Copy of biographic sketch submitted to the Farm Credit Administration of Berkeley dated April 6, 1938,  in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref>  From 1927 to 1928 Mallory was an assistant in horticulture at the University of British Columbia, and in 1929 worked as secretary of the British Columbia Fruit Growers.<ref>Biography, dated July 1, 1930, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref>\n\nMallory began working for the United States [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] in 1931, initially for the [[United States Department of Agriculture|Department of Agriculture]] as assistant [[Commissioner#U.S._Department_of_Agriculture|agricultural commissioner]] in Marseille, to which position he was appointed June 15, 1931.<ref name=\"prob-rpt\">Report on Probationary Appointee, Standard Form No. 17, dated November 14, 1931, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref> Mallory was selected for this position on the basis of his expertise in analysis of horticultural products.<ref name=\"nils-memo\">Memorandum for the Secretary, dated March 26, 1931, from Nils A. Olsen, Chief, Bureau of Agricultural Economics, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref> \n\nFrom July 1933 to August 1934 Mallory was assigned to Washington as an associate agricultural economist in the Agricultural Adjustment Administration of USDA, working on farm credit issues.<ref name=\"prob-rpt\"/><ref>Application for Employment, Farm Credit Administration of Berkeley, dated April 6, 1938, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref>  In August 1934 he was assigned to Paris as assistant [[agricultural attach\u00e9]].  Effective June 2, 1938, he was designated acting agricultural attach\u00e9, and as of June 1, 1939, he was appointed agricultural attach\u00e9 at Paris.<ref>Memorandum for Mr. Roy F. Hendrickson from L.A. Wheeler dated May 3, 1939, in personnel records of Lester D. Mallory at the National Personnel Records Center, St. Louis, Missouri</ref>  \n\n[[Image:390519 Wallace appt Mallory agatt.JPG|thumb|left|Letter from Secretary of Agriculture Henry Wallace to the Secretary of State advising of Mallory's appointment as agricultural attach\u00e9 at Paris. Source: National Archives and Records Administration]]\n\nMallory was evacuated to the United States with the outbreak of World War II in September 1939 and reassigned as the first U.S. agricultural attach\u00e9 in Mexico City.  At that time he was commissioned a [[Foreign Service Officer]] in the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]], as the [[Foreign Agricultural Service]] was abolished and agricultural attach\u00e9s were transferred from USDA to State in that year. \n\nMallory subsequently served in liberated Paris, from Christmas Eve 1944 until mid-1945. During his tour of duty in Paris, Mallory was granted permission by the Department of State to marry a foreign national, Eleanor Mercedes Struck y Bulnes, whom he had met in Mexico City.<ref>This correspondence is stored in Mallory's personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref>   He then returned to the U.S., where he was liaison officer between USDA's Office of Foreign Agricultural Relations and the U.S. Department of State.  Mallory was assigned to [[Havana]] as counselor of embassy (deputy chief of mission) in 1947 and in 1949 to [[Buenos Aires]] in the same capacity.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>Foreign Service Operations Memorandum dated June 13, 1949, regarding departure from post of Lester D. MALLORY, FSO, in the personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref>  On August 23, 1950, President Truman appointed Mallory to the personal rank of Minister.<ref name=nara-annex>Letter to Lester D. Mallory from Harry S Truman dated August 23, 1950, personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref>\n\nMallory served as [[United States Ambassador to Jordan|Ambassador to Jordan]] from 1953 to 1958 and to [[United States Ambassador to Guatemala|Guatemala]] in 1958 and 1959. During his tour of duty in Jordan, on July 20, 1955, Mallory was promoted to the then-highest Foreign Service rank, [[Senior_Foreign_Service#History|Career Minister]].<ref>Notification of Personnel Action dated July 20, 1955, \"Promotion to Class of Career Minister,\" personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref>  Mallory was a [[Assistant Secretary of State for Western Hemisphere Affairs|Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for Western Hemisphere Affairs]] in 1960 and retired from the State Department on October 31 of that year.<ref>Letter from Christian A. Herter to Lester Mallory dated October 14, 1960, personnel records of Lester Mallory in the National Archives, National Personnel Records Center Annex, Valmeyer, Illinois</ref> \n\nMallory then joined the [[Inter-American Development Bank]], working in Washington, D.C., [[Costa Rica]], and [[Panama]], and helped establish the [[anthropology]] department at the [[University of Guadalajara]], Mexico.  In 1961 the Guatemalan government presented him with the [[Order of the Quetzal]].<ref>''FAS Letter'', April 1961</ref>\n\nHe lived in [[Lake Forest, California]] and died following a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at Saddleback Hospital in [[Laguna Hills, California]].  The conference room of the Foreign Agricultural Service's office in the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City is named in his honor. His oral history interview was published by the Association for Diplomatic Studies and Training.\n\n\n\n=== His role in the embargo against Cuba ===\n\nAs Deputy Assistant Secretary, he wrote an internal memo on April 6, 1960 to initiate the [[United States embargo against Cuba]]. Mallory proposed denying money and supplies to Cuba, decreasing their wages, and bringing about hunger and desperation. Later that year, the Eisenhower administration instituted the embargo.\n\nIn a secret memorandum, declassified in 1991, Mallory wrote on April 6, 1960: \"Most Cubans support Castro\u2026There is no effective political opposition (\u2026) The only possible way to make the government lose domestic support is by provoking disappointment and discouragement through economic dissatisfaction and hardships (\u2026) Every possible means should be immediately used to weaken the economic life (\u2026) denying Cuba funds and supplies to reduce nominal and real salaries with the objective of provoking hunger, desperation and the overthrow of the government.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{NARA}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web| title=Association for Diplomatic Studies and Training Oral Histories | url=http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/collections/diplomacy/ | accessdate=2009-03-23}} (use the search engine for a \"Full Text\" search on \"Lester Mallory\" in quotes)\n* {{cite web | title=Direct Link to Oral History of Lester D. Mallory | url=http://www.adst.org/OH%20TOCs/Mallory,%20Lester%20.toc.pdf | accessdate=2016-09-06}}\n* {{cite web| title=Lester Mallory, 90, Former U.S. Envoy (obituary) | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/02/world/lester-mallory-90-former-us-envoy.html | publisher=New York Times | date=July 2, 1994 }}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Joseph C. Green]] | after=[[Parker T. Hart]] | title=[[United States Ambassador to Jordan]] | years=December 1, 1953&ndash;January 11, 1958}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Edward J. Sparks]] | after=[[John J. Muccio]] | title=[[United States Ambassador to Guatemala]] | years=February 27, 1958&ndash;November 11, 1959}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mallory, Lester DeWitt}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Jordan]]\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:Order of the Quetzal]]\n[[Category:United States Foreign Service personnel]]\n", "name_user": "107.242.117.13", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHis role in the embargo against Cuba)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lester_D._Mallory"}
{"title_page": "Barry Bostwick", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Barry Bostwick\n| image              = Barry Bostwick at GalaxyCon Louisville 2019.jpg\n| caption            = Bostwick at [[GalaxyCon]] Louisville in 2019\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1945|2|24}}<!--- 1945 is correct, according to California Birth Records --->\n| birth_place        = [[San Mateo, California|San Mateo]], California\n| birth_name         = Barry Knapp Bostwick\n| occupation         = Actor, singer\n| education          = [[Alliant International University|Alliant International University, San Diego]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| years_active       = 1970\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Stacey Nelkin]]|1987|1991|reason=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Sherri Jensen<br>|1994}}\n| children           = 2\n}}\n\n'''Barry Knapp Bostwick''' (born February 24, 1945<!--- 1945 is correct, according to California Birth Records --->) is an American stage and screen actor and singer. He is best known for portraying Brad Majors in the [[Musical film|musical]] [[comedy horror]] ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'' (1975) and Mayor Randall Winston in the [[sitcom]] ''[[Spin City]]'' (1996\u20132002). He has also had considerable success in [[musical theatre]], winning a [[Tony Award]] for his role in ''[[The Robber Bridegroom (musical)|The Robber Bridegroom]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBostwick was born in [[San Mateo, California]]. He is the son of Elizabeth \"Betty\" (n\u00e9e Defendorf), a housewife, and Henry \"Bud\" Bostwick, a city planner and actor.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Barry Bostwick Biography | work=filmreference | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/41/Barry-Bostwick.html | year=2008 | accessdate=2008-06-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |title=Barry Bostwick Biography |work=Yahoo! Movies |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800021649/bio |year=2008 |accessdate=2008-06-07 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927210930/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800021649/bio |archivedate=2006-09-27 |df= }}</ref> His only sibling, Henry \"Pete\" Bostwick, was killed in a car accident on July 20, 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/san-mateo-times/1973-07-20/|title=NewspaperArchive\u00ae - Newspaper Archives, Obituaries & Family History|website=Newspaperarchive.com|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> Bostwick attended San Diego's [[United States International University]] in 1967, majoring in acting, got his start on the Hillbarn Theatre stage now located in Foster City, and worked for a time as a circus performer. He also attended NYU's [[Tisch School of the Arts#Graduate Acting Program|Graduate Acting Program]], graduating in 1968.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=NYU Graduate Acting Alumni | url=http://gradacting.tisch.nyu.edu/object/ga_alumbios.html | year=2011  | accessdate=2011-12-01}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1970, Bostwick was a member of a pop group called The Klowns, assembled and promoted by [[Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus]], whose members performed wearing stylized clown makeup and costumes. Their sole album, released in 1970, was produced by [[Jeff Barry]], and generated a minor ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' hit single, \"Lady Love\".\n\nBostwick replaced C.C. Courtney in the musical ''[[Salvation (musical)|Salvation]]''. His next stage appearance was in the 1971 rock opera ''[[Soon (musical)|Soon]]'', which closed after three performances. In 1972, Bostwick originated the role of bad boy [[Danny Zuko]] in the stage production of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'', earning a [[Tony Award]] nomination for his performance. This was followed by a voice role as Terr in the English-dubbed version of ''[[Fantastic Planet]]'' in 1973. He later starred with [[Tim Curry]] and [[Susan Sarandon]] in ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'' (1975) portraying the character of Brad Majors. He also won a [[Tony Award]] for his performance in the 1977 musical ''[[The Robber Bridegroom (musical)|The Robber Bridegroom]]''. In 1981, Bostwick starred in the [[Foul Play (TV series)|TV series adaptation]] of the 1978 movie ''[[Foul Play (1978 film)|Foul Play]]'', with his role modeled after [[Chevy Chase]]'s and co-star [[Deborah Raffin]] in [[Goldie Hawn]]'s part. The following year, he starred in ''[[Megaforce]]''. Bostwick starred, along with [[Carl Weintraub]], as Rick Armstrong in the short-lived ABC sitcom ''[[Dads (1986 TV series)|Dads]]'' during the 1986-87 season.  From 1996 to 2002, Bostwick portrayed Randall Winston, the mayor of [[New York City]] in the [[situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Spin City]]'' opposite [[Michael J. Fox]] and his successor, [[Charlie Sheen]]. In 2006, Bostwick replaced [[Peter Scolari]] as Mr. Tyler, the father of [[Amanda Bynes]]' and [[Jennie Garth]]'s lead characters, on ''[[What I Like About You (TV series)|What I Like About You]]''.<ref name=\"imdb.com\">{{IMDb title|0759389|What I Like About You}}</ref>\n\nBostwick had a recurring role between 2004 and 2007 on ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''. He has also had leading roles in various mini-series, including ''[[George Washington (miniseries)|George Washington]]'', its sequel ''[[George Washington II: The Forging of a Nation]]'', ''[[Scruples (TV miniseries)|Scruples]]'', ''[[A Woman of Substance (miniseries)|A Woman of Substance]]'', ''[[War and Remembrance]]'', and ''[[Judith Krantz's Till We Meet Again|Till We Meet Again]]''.\n\nBostwick served as host of the nationally televised annual ''[[Fourth of July|Capitol Fourth]]'' celebration on the [[National Mall]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] for eight years. Bostwick was also seen in a [[Pepsi Twist]] commercial. In the ''[[Cold Case (TV series)|Cold Case]]'' episode \"Creatures of the Night\", in which he is the main suspect, the theme of the episode revolves around ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'', which is among his best-known performances to date.\n\nIn 2003, Bostwick appeared on ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'' as a patient diagnosed with [[prostate cancer]], a disease Bostwick had in real life. In 2008, he appeared in an episode of TV series ''[[Ugly Betty]]'' as an attorney to the Meade family. In 2007, Bostwick gained a recurring role, as Grandpa Clyde Flynn on the animated television series, ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]''. Bostwick is also the spokesperson for [[Optimum Voice]].<ref>{{cite web|author=  |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VdMJ5P8cSNI |title=Optimum Voice Commercial with Barry Bostwick |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2011-10-10}}</ref> In June 2009 he played Father Jimmy, the ineffective exorcist in the independent horror comedy ''The Selling'', written by Gabriel Diani and directed by Emily Lou.\n\nOther television credits include guest appearances in ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'', ''[[The Golden Palace]]'', ''[[Grace Under Fire (TV series)|Grace Under Fire]]'', and ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]''.\n\nBostwick was supposed to appear on season 3 of ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]'' as \"the Captain\", a father of the [[Addison Montgomery]] character, but had to resign due to a scheduling conflict.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fancast.com/blogs/matts-tv-news/private-practice-scoop-addisons-dad-is-sent-from-heaven/ |title='Private Practice' Scoop: Addison's Dad Is Sent from 'Heaven' &#124; XFINITY TV News |publisher=Fancast.com |date=2009-10-12 |accessdate=2011-10-10 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213120723/http://www.fancast.com/blogs/matts-tv-news/private-practice-scoop-addisons-dad-is-sent-from-heaven/ |archivedate=2009-12-13 |df= }}</ref> In 2011, Bostwick portrayed a small town sheriff in the [[John Landis]]-produced thriller ''[[Some Guy Who Kills People]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1568341/|title=Some Guy Who Kills People|publisher=IMDB}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BarryBostwickApr09.jpg|thumb|Bostwick at the premiere for ''[[Earth (2007 film)|Earth]]'' in April 2009]]\nIn October 2010, Bostwick briefly appeared in [[The Rocky Horror Glee Show|the ''Rocky Horror''-themed]] ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b199812_exclusive_rocky_horror_original.html|title=Exclusive: ''Rocky Horror'' Original Castmembers to Appear in ''Glee''{{'s}} Tribute Episode|first=Kristin|last=Dos Santos|authorlink=Kristin Dos Santos|date=September 10, 2010|publisher=[[E! Online|E!]]|accessdate=September 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSince 2009, Bostwick has had a recurring role as Roger Frank on the sitcom ''[[Cougar Town]]'' which stars [[Courteney Cox]]. In season 3 of the show we learn that Bostwick's character has become mayor of the town the comedy is set in, Gulf Haven. In 2015, he starred in [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]'s segment of the [[anthology film]] ''[[Tales of Halloween]]'', which was his second time acting under Bousman after ''[[The Devil's Carnival]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/86332/tales-halloween-interview-spotlight-barry-bostwick/|title=Tales of Halloween Interview Spotlight: Barry Bostwick - Dread Central|date=4 February 2015|website=Dreadcentral.com|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> and appeared in the [[comedy horror]] film ''Helen Keller vs. Nightwolves''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/94274/helen-keller-vs-nightwolves-sees-a-teaser-trailer/|title=Helen Keller vs. Nightwolves Sees a Teaser Trailer - Dread Central|date=24 March 2015|website=Dreadcentral.com|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> In 2015 he portrayed Collin Winthrop, father of the Gig Harbor Killer, in the season-ending ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'' episode \"The End Game\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4145952/|title=The End Game|date=15 February 2015|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=8 October 2017|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> He has also had a return to cult musical horror films in the form of [[Terrance Zdunich]]'s ''[[Alleluia! The Devil's Carnival]]'', which is a sequel to the 2012 short film ''[[The Devil's Carnival]]'', which he was not previously a cast member of, being a newcomer to the franchise.\n\n==Personal life==\nBostwick married [[Stacey Nelkin]] in 1987, and they were divorced in 1991. He married his second wife Sherri Ellen Jensen in 1993; they have two children, a son and a daughter.<ref>Lipton, Michael L. [https://people.com/archive/serial-dad-vol-47-no-9/ \"Serial Dad\"] ''People'', March 10, 1997</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Bostwick was diagnosed with [[prostate cancer]], and had his prostate removed in July 1997.<ref>Moran Reed W. [http://www.usrf.org/news/Barry_Bostwick.html \"Barry Bostwick advises on prostate cancer\"] ''USA Today'', March 9, 2002</ref> In 2004, he won the [[Gilda Radner]] Courage Award from the [[Roswell Park Cancer Institute]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Select filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Jennifer on My Mind]]''\n| Minstrel #1\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Fantastic Planet]]''\n| Narrator\n| Voice role\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''Road Movie''\n| Hank\n|\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]''\n| Brad Majors\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Movie Movie]]''\n| Johnny Danko / Dick Cummings\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Megaforce]]''\n| Commander Ace Hunter\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1993 || ''[[Eight Hundred Leagues Down the Amazon]]''\n| Garral\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Weekend at Bernie's II]]''\n| Arthur Hummel\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''In the Heat of Passion II: Unfaithful''\n| Phillip\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1996\n| ''[[The Secret Agent Club]]''\n| Vincent Scarletti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Spy Hard]]''\n| Norm Coleman\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2003\n| ''[[101 Dalmatians II: Patch's London Adventure]]''\n