\n| ''[[Some Guy Who Kills People]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Evans, David and Scott Michaels. ''Rocky Horror: Concept to Cult''. London: Sanctuary, 2002.\n* Lipton, Michael A. and Nancy Matsumoto. \u201cSerial Dad: Michael J. Fox Looks Up to 6\u20194\u201d Actor\u201d. People March 10, 1997: 99.\n* Uhry, Alfred. \"The Trail of the Robber B\". The Robber Bridegroom CD Liner Notes 1998: 2.\n* Hunt, Paula. \"Bostwick Tells Story of Survival\". Express-News, March 6, 2006.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|23289}}\n* {{IMDb name|960}}\n* {{amg name|7552}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Barry Bostwick\n|list =\n{{GoldenGlobeSupportingActorTV 1970-1989}}\n{{TonyAward MusicalLeadActor 1976-2000}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bostwick, Barry}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:People from San Mateo, California]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:United States International University alumni]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barry_Bostwick"}
{"title_page": "William Orbit", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = William Mark Wainwright\n| alias               = William Orbit\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1956|12|15|df=y}}\n| origin              = [[Shoreditch]], [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]], [[London]], England\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Electronica]]|[[trip hop]]|[[Ambient music|ambient]]|[[Trance music|trance]]|[[house music|house]]|[[downtempo]]|[[intelligent dance music|IDM]]|[[Pop music|pop]]|[[orchestral]]}}\n| occupation          = {{hlist|Composer|record producer|artist}}\n| instrument          = {{hlist|[[Keyboard (instrument)|Keyboards]]|[[guitar]]|[[percussion]]}}\n| years_active        = 1982\u2013present\n| label               = {{hlist|[[I.R.S. Records|I.R.S.]]|[[EMI]]|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]|N-GRAM|[[Maverick (company)|Maverick]]|[[Sanctuary Records|Sanctuary]]|Kobalt|[[Decca Records|Decca]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]|Guerilla}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[Torch Song (band)|Torch Song]]|[[Bassomatic]]|[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|[[Strange Cargo (band)|Strange Cargo]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.williamorbit.com|williamorbit.com}}\n}}\n\n'''William Orbit''' (born '''William Mark Wainwright'''; 15 December 1956)<ref name=\"ContempMusicians\">\"William Orbit.\" ''Contemporary Musicians''. Vol. 30. Farmington Hills, MI: Gale, 2000. Retrieved via ''Biography in Context'' database, 2017-05-07. Available online [http://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/orbit-william via ''Encyclopedia.com''].</ref> is an English musician, composer and record producer who has sold 200 million recordings worldwide of his own work, his production and songwriting work. He is a recipient of multiple [[Grammy Award]]s, [[Ivor Novello Awards]] and other music industry awards.\n\n==Early life==\n\nOrbit (Wainwright) was raised in [[Shoreditch]], in [[East London]].<ref name=\"ContempMusicians\"/> His parents were both schoolteachers; he was the older of two sons.<ref name=\"ContempMusicians\"/> Despite his parents' objections, he left school at the age of 16, and subsisted for a number of years in various low-paying jobs, while seeking an outlet for his creativity.<ref name=\"ContempMusicians\"/><ref name=\"ContempMusicians\"/> Around this time, while rooming with a friend who was trying to start a recording studio, Orbit found his musical calling.<ref name=\"ContempMusicians\"/>\n\n==Torch Song==\n\nIn 1980 Orbit teamed up with [[Laurie Mayer (composer)|Laurie Mayer]] and Grant Gilbert to form the electronic/synth group Torch Song. They initially self-released recordings in an audio cassette series, generated from their home-built studio in a disused school in [[Notting Hill Gate]], in London, alongside the Grand Union Canal. [[Neville Brody]], the graphic designer, joined the band for a period. Orbit and Mayer were also visual artists and created a series of art magazines called ''The Ralph Hoover Guide'' in which he drew surrealist cartoons. The issues were sold at various London galleries and at the Institute of Contemporary Arts in The Mall. Richard Law, who was the A&R for IRS Records, was a follower of their music and aesthetic, and took it to industry mogul [[Miles Copeland III|Miles Copeland]], who had discovered and managed [[the Police]] and [[the Bangles]] in 1981. When Copeland signed them to the label the deal enabled them to build their ideal studio.  There they recorded two albums and four singles,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/10950-Torch-Song|title=Torch Song|website=Discogs|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref> the most successful being the dance chart hit \"Prepare to Energize\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Torch-Song-Prepare-To-Energize/master/131686|title=Torch Song - Prepare To Energize|website=Discogs|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref> which was featured in the film ''[[Bachelor Party (1984 film)|Bachelor Party]]''.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0086927/soundtrack \"Bachelor Party (1984) Soundtracks\"]. [[IMDb]]. Retrieved 2017-05-07.</ref> They also composed the soundtrack to the ice hockey movie ''[[Youngblood (1986 film)|Youngblood]]'',<ref>YouTube clip: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FWabOW6fVyw \"William Orbit - Opening Score(from Youngblood Soundtrack)\"], ''[[YouTube]]'', Sept 12, 2012.</ref> starring [[Rob Lowe]] and [[Keanu Reeves]], and recorded another song, written by colleague Rico Conning, \"White Night\" which was used in \u2018Texas Chainsaw Massacre 2\u2019.<ref>YouTube clip: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eOH5yXA5mgI \"Texas Chainsaw Massacre Part 2 Soundtrack White Night By Torch Song\"], ''[[YouTube]]'', Sept 12, 2012.</ref>\n\nThis first incarnation of Guerilla Studios had a Trident 80B mixing desk and Otari MTR90 MKII 24 track  (2 inch tape) multitrack housed in a back garden on the canals of [[Little Venice, London|Little Venice]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/label/277232-Guerilla-Studios|title=Guerilla Studios|website=Discogs|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref> in [[Paddington]], and they also ran it as a commercial enterprise.\n\n==Productions and remixes==\n\nCollaborations and productions included [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Britney Spears]], [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[U2]], [[Katie Melua]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Beth Orton]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]], [[The Joy Formidable]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[All Saints (group)|All Saints]], [[Kraftwerk]], and [[Sugababes]]. When working with [[Beck (musician)|Beck]], the two of them wrote a song for Pink, \"[[Feel Good Time]],\" which Orbit then produced for the soundtrack for the 2000 film ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]''.\n\nHe produced the album ''[[13 (Blur album)|13]]'' by Britpop group [[Blur (band)|Blur]], in London and [[Reykjav\u00edk]], [[Iceland]].\n\nOrbit had created remixes for Madonna previously such as \"[[Justify My Love]]\" and \"[[Erotica (song)|Erotica]]\" but he didn't meet her personally until 1997. That summer and autumn they wrote together and produced her multi-Grammy/award-winning seventh album ''[[Ray of Light]]''. The album took four months to record and it was the longest she ever spent recording an album. It was released on 22 February 1998.\n\nIn 2000, Orbit continued his songwriting for Madonna's 2000 album ''[[Music (Madonna album)|Music]]'' recorded at The Hit Factory in New York and also co-wrote and performed the song \"[[Beautiful Stranger]]\".\nThe two joined up again for her 2012 album ''[[MDNA (album)|MDNA]]'', co-writing and producing six of the tracks on the album. \"[[Masterpiece (Madonna song)|Masterpiece]]\" won a [[Golden Globe]] for Best Original Song in the  Miramax movie \"W.E.\", at the 69th Golden Globe Awards.\n\n==Classical work==\nInspired and encouraged by Rob Dickins, his first commercial release in this genre was ''[[Pieces in a Modern Style]]''. It was originally released in May 1995 on Orbit\u2019s N-Gram Recordings label, and then again in 2000 by Warner Music in the UK and Europe, and on Maverick in the U.S. The album reached No 2 in the UK album charts. The first single release from the album was \u2018Barber\u2019s [[Adagio for Strings]]\u2019, and a dance remix of the track by Dutch DJ [[Ferry Corsten]] was hugely successful. The single reached number 4<ref name=\"chartstats\"/><ref>UK Official Singles Charts [http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/19991212/7501/ \"Official Singles Chart Top 100, 12th Dec 1999\"], ''[http://www.officialcharts.com/]''</ref> in the national singles chart. A follow up album,  \u2032[[Pieces in a Modern Style 2]]\u2032 came out in 2010, and was released as a two-disc set on the Decca label. He worked with German countertenor Andreas Scholl<ref>Andreas Scholl Discography. [http://www.andreasschollsociety.org/discography.htm \"Andreas Scholl Discography\"], ''[http://www.andreasschollsociety.org/]''</ref> on an interpretation of Henry Purcell\u2019s Dido\u2019s Lament which was featured on the album.\n\nIn 2007 he took part in Alex Poots\u2019 Manchester International Festival, and composed a symphonic work in nine movements \u2018Orchestral Suite\u2019 which was performed by the BBC Philharmonic Orchestra, augmented by additional harps, pianos and percussion, and with The Manchester Chorale, conducted by Alexander Shelley at Bridgewater Hall.<ref>Aspden, Peter (June June&nbsp;22, 2007). \"[https://www.ft.com/content/89920928-20be-11dc-8d50-000b5df10621 Alluring echoes of Hoxton]\". ''[[Financial Times#FT Weekend|Financial Times: FT Weekend, Life&nbsp;&amp; Arts]]''. www.ft.com. Retrieved 2017-05-07.</ref>\n\n==Live performance/media/DJ work==\nDuring the N'Gram period, he directed a showcase of the label at Queen Elizabeth Hall<ref>Performance: WILLIAM ORBIT Royal Festival Hall, London. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/performance-william-orbit-royal-festival-hall-london-1593122.html \"Performance: WILLIAM ORBIT Royal Festival Hall, London\"], 'Independent', Monday 24 July 1995.</ref> on London's Southbank. The acts included [[Caroline Lavelle]], The Electric Chamber (which performed the Pieces album) Strange Cargo, and [[Torch Song (band)|Torch Song]]. Orbit included a range of power tools and angle grinders as part of the musical ensemble.\n\nIn 2001 he took part in the Stockhausen Electronic Festival<ref>The sound of discord. [https://www.theguardian.com/education/2001/sep/29/arts.highereducation3 \"William Orbit, who appears alongside Stockhausen in next month's Elektronic Festival \"], 'The Guardian', 29th Sept 2001.</ref> at the Barbican Theatre.\n\nIn 2013 he took part in the London Electronic Arts Festival. <ref>William Orbit confirmed for first London Electronic Arts Festival. [http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Music-Review/georgio-moroder-and-william-orbit-confirmed-for-first-london-electronic-arts-festival \"Georgio Moroder and William Orbit confirmed for first London Electronic Arts Festival\"], 'Indie London', Nov 2013.</ref>\n\nHe participated in the Liberatum International Cultural Festival<ref>Carrera Presents Liberatum Hong Kong International Festival of Culture. [http://www.lisabakerltd.com/blog/liberatum-hong-kong/ \"Carrera Presents Liberatum Hong Kong International Festival of Culture\"], 'Lisa Baker Associates Limited', 22 March 2012.</ref> in Russia, during which he performed in Moscow and Novosibirsk, Siberia, and gave lectures.\n\nMore recently Orbit has deejayed at various clubs in London and Ibiza and at Buckingham Palace<ref>William Orbit at Buckingham Palace. [http://www.irishexaminer.com/examviral/celeb-life/william-orbit-played-the-national-anthem-at-buckingham-palace-party-334650.html \"William Orbit played the national anthem at Buckingham Palace party\"], 'irishexaminer', Thursday, 4 June 2015.</ref> for Her Majesty The Queen\u2019s annual staff and family Christmas party.\n\nIn 2013 William worked with [[Britney Spears]] and [[Will.i.am]] on her album ''[[Britney Jean]]'', with fellow songwriters [[Ana Diaz (Swedish singer)|Ana Diaz]] and Dan Traynor with whom he wrote and produced the track \"Alien\". \nHe was a writer and producer on the [[Chris Brown]] song \"Don't Wake Me Up\" which was recorded at Record Plant in LA and for which he received an ASCAP<ref>ASCAP Awards. [http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/prs/2013/songawards.aspx \"ASCAP Awards 2013\"], 'ASCAP', 2013.</ref> award in 2013. The song has had 180 Million views on YouTube.<ref>YouTube. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QOowQeKyNkQ \"ASCAP Awards 2013\"], 'Chris Brown - Don't Wake Me Up', June 2012.</ref>\nThis was followed by a production of the Queen track \"[[There Must Be More to Life Than This]]\", which featured archive vocals by [[Freddie Mercury]] and [[Michael Jackson]].  Orbit went on to produce another Queen song, \"[[Let Me in Your Heart Again]]\".\nIn 2015 his composition \"The Name of the Wave\" was used in the Oscar winning documentary ''[[Amy (2015 film)|Amy]]'' directed by Asif Kapadia.<ref>Amy (soundtrack). [[Amy (soundtrack)|\"Amy\"]], 'Amy (soundtrack)', Oct 2015.</ref>\n\nHe performed in 2015 in [[Almaty]], Kazakhstan, and at a gala at Banqueting House in London's Whitehall for the charity Together For Short Lives, a group that sponsors and supports children with terminal illness and their families.<ref>The midsummer ball. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150707070932/http://www.togetherforshortlives.org.uk/get_involved/the_midsummer_ball \"Together for Short Lives\u2019 Midsummer Ball\"], 'The Midsummer Ball', 3 June 2015.</ref>\n\n==Solo discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=text-align:center;\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:250px;\"| Album\n! colspan=\"3\"| Chart positions\n|-\n! style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]] <br /><ref name=\"chartstats\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/|title=The Official Charts Company: William Orbit|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2011-04-29|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tobias Zywietz |url=http://www.zobbel.de/ |title=The Official Zobbel Homepage |publisher=Zobbel.de |date= |accessdate=2012-04-18}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]] <br /><ref name=\"australian\">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=William+%D8rbit|title= Discography William Orbit|publisher=Australian-Charts.com|accessdate=2011-04-29}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]] <br /><ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p13868|pure_url=yes}}|title=William Orbit > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums|publishe